{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"This is a cross-module handoff check (request builder -> API client payload). A unit test of only the builder can miss wiring/serialization mismatch at the boundary. System is rejected because behavior text does not require real HTTP/provider contract verification, only payload contents before/at dispatch. Agentic/Workflow are rejected because no model decision quality or multi-agent sequence is under test.","test_description":"Use the real request-construction path with a stub/fake API transport that captures the outbound payload; assert every configured taxonomy label is present in each dispatched request.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure risk is at module boundary coupling (API response parsing + taxonomy guard + returned value). Unit-only normalization tests can miss adapter/mapper wiring. System is rejected because no real network/external contract is explicitly required; a controlled fake response can reproduce the failure. Agentic/Workflow are rejected because correctness here is guard logic on an invalid value, not model output quality.","test_description":"Run end-to-end inside process: feed a fake provider response containing an out-of-taxonomy label through the real response parsing/normalization path and assert returned label is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","required_reality_check_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior is explicitly a deterministic normalization-function property on identical inputs; no boundary, I/O, or orchestration risk is required by the text. Higher levels add little new reality signal for this specific invariant.","test_description":"Pure-function/property-style test: call normalization repeatedly with the same raw response fixture and assert identical final label each run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","required_reality_check_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on repeated live AI-provider outputs and consistency under model nondeterminism. Mocks cannot reveal real-model variance, so Integration is insufficient. Workflow is rejected because this is repeated single-step classification calls, not a multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Execute multiple real provider calls for identical input/taxonomy over a bounded window; record raw responses and final labels; assert label stability when raw provider response class is unchanged, and only permit label change when provider response changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"This is orchestration/state handoff across local components (budget config + tokenizer/estimator + request dispatcher). Unit tests of policy logic alone can miss enforcement at dispatch boundary. System is rejected because behavior text targets pre-dispatch enforcement, not real external response/side-effect proof. Agentic/Workflow are rejected because no model-output dependence is required.","test_description":"Drive the real request-building/dispatch code with over-budget and within-budget inputs; assert truncation/rejection policy is applied before any send path and that under-budget requests proceed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","required_reality_check_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires a real AI-provider call and uses provider-reported usage, which can vary with model behavior/completion characteristics; a mock can hide true usage behavior. System is plausible for external contract checks, but Agentic is kept because the execution path and measured outcome depend on real model call behavior, not just transport plumbing. Workflow is rejected because it is one call-level behavior, not multi-step agent sequencing.","test_description":"Run real classification calls for representative documents against the live provider and assert reported token usage per call is <= configured budget; repeat enough times to account for live-model variability.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.3,"Agentic":0.62,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry orchestration across components (error classifier + backoff/wait + retry dispatcher + final return). Unit tests on retry function alone can miss wiring/order/state transfer. System is rejected because behavior text does not require proving real HTTP timing semantics; deterministic simulated rate-limit responses can validate logic. Agentic/Workflow are rejected because no dependence on model decision quality or multi-agent chain is specified.","test_description":"Use a fake provider client sequence (rate-limit error then success) through real module logic; assert wait/backoff is invoked, retry occurs, and caller receives success instead of immediate error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.23,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
